      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/output-comparison-mrl2-criteria-001",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RHI) is compared quantitatively against experimental measurements at all 5 validated operating points. Maximum prediction error is 13.2% (conservative over-prediction), within the ±20% acceptance criterion. Uncertainty bands (±8.4% at k=2) are computed via Monte Carlo propagation and do not overlap zero error, confirming consistent conservative bias. Comparison methodology follows ASME V&V 20 guidelines. Achieved Level 2 meets the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-mrl2-criteria-001",
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest — the relative hemolysis index (RHI) — directly maps to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RHI < 1.0) and is the same metric used in predicate device comparison. The CFD-derived hemolysis integral (power-law Giersiepen-Wurzinger applied to Lagrangian particle tracking) is a recognized surrogate for NIH-normalized hemolysis index validated in peer-reviewed literature. The QoI is directly relevant to the COU decision (worst-case operating condition identification). Achieved Level 2 meets the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
