      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/solver-error-scopeout-mrl2",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, explicit solver error quantification beyond code verification is not required. The RANS k-omega SST solver is a well-established turbulence model with extensive published validation for rotating machinery flows. Residual convergence criteria (all residuals < 1e-5) and mass balance checks (< 0.01%) are applied to every simulation. Solver error is bounded by the code verification results (MMS, observed order 1.88–1.97) and is not a dominant uncertainty source for the hemolysis QoI at this risk level. Scoped out per MRL 2 assessment plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/use-error-scopeout-mrl2",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2, formal use error analysis is not required. Simulation setup was performed by trained CFD analysts following documented standard operating procedures. Independent peer review of boundary conditions, solver settings, and post-processing scripts was completed prior to production runs. Simulation files are version-controlled and archived. Use error risk is mitigated through procedural controls adequate for MRL 2. Scoped out per MRL 2 assessment plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/model-form-scopeout-mrl2",
      "rationale": "Formal model form uncertainty quantification is not required at MRL 2. The RANS k-omega SST turbulence model is the established standard for centrifugal pump hemolysis CFD per FDA guidance and published literature (Hariharan et al. 2011, Stewart et al. 2012). The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis correlation is the most widely used and validated power-law model for this device class. Model form adequacy is supported by the validation evidence (13.2% maximum error, conservative bias) within the declared operating envelope. Scoped out per MRL 2 assessment plan."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
